>>28962811
Those are practically nonexistent. And mostly just people being chicken shit about "muh clots". For potential clots you need to lowdose a anticoagulant like baby aspirin (81mg), if you have an active case of DVT (I did in my right leg) you take shit like warfarin and after a couple of months you switch to aspirin when it's gone. Clots really become a problem only if you have CHRONIC intestinal bleeding.
There's very few people who have actual chronic intestinal bleeding and DVT at the same time, to a point that doctors write papers about people like them.
Cases like HHT (hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia) + DVT. Do you know what's hilarious about them? A part of treatment for HHT even in males is hormonal treatment with raloxifen, yeah, the same ralox femboys use for transitioning. Shit only gets complicated in later stages of HHT, that's when managing both HHT and DVT at the same time becomes really problematic, but at that point transitioning is the least of your concerns because you're practically dying.
And if your intestinal bleeding is caused by some fucking intestinal ulcer, just stfu. You're just being lazy because it's not even a chronic thing, it's like the most easily treatable case of intestinal bleeding, shit goes away in under a month with proper medication. Then a low dose of a mild anticoagulant becomes a nonissue.
"Muh clots" are literally a case of making a mountain out of a molehill.

Ohhh I see I see
Well, replacing sub with oral is a bit problematic, bcs you're going from higher avg/peak lvls w/sub to a lot lower with same mg sub to oral e2 dose.
to explain, oral takes awhile to buildup e2 lvls as your body is building up a reservoir of various sulfated/conjugated/weaker forms of estrogens that build up, which converts back to e2 making e2 lvls nice and steady plus higher e2 lvls on avg than single dose (takes a few weeks), and so if u rely on oral e2 without building up u can suddenly spike T lvls due to lacking antigonadatropin action of higher e2 like sub does.
so, it very well could of been a spike in T lvls, even just mid/high female T lvls, but that change from likely near zero T would be a bit of a shock to your system as likely sensitized ARs due to low T lvls for awhile+cypro being an AR antagonist

my advice in the future is to titrate your dose when changing it, so avoid that sudden shock like u experienced, and with oral e2 u wanna build up lvls first b4 relying on it

Goal of the thread: Make a shopping list of things that you need, consider if there is any self care things you might be missing!

>What is this thread for?
Getting better is hard, and sucks. A lot. It does not get easier doing it alone.
Share resources and experiences with combating depression, anxiety, personal issues, achieving or maintaining a healthy weight, etc.
>Why is this thread /lgbt/?
Struggles with mental and physical health are an indisputable part of /lgbt/ life, be it from dysphoria, social pressure, heartbreak, or just unfortunate lifestyle choices.
>Notes to consider:
Please be civil. Shame is your greatest enemy in fighting urges of self abuse (be it sh, drugs, or just self deprecation). Relapsing into bad and unhealthy habits is to be expected, the goal is to increase the average amount of time it takes between relapses. Any improvement is a victory no matter how small. Your worth and right to get better are non-negotiable. And most importantly:
WE ARE NOT THERAPISTS, WE DON'T REPLACE MEDICATION
>Note on advice
Generic advice won't necessarily help you in particular, but for those it does it is an essential foundation to build future progress on, not a miracle cure. Do not underestimate the effects subtle changes to your lifestyle can have. Try first, keep us posted on your progress, build from there.

If any resource below is unhelpful, please let me know. I can't assert their quality on my own.

>>28958206
>what if i dont like reading?
Then I would suppose you have not been putting it off. Remember, you can pick and choose tasks!
>i dont want to do that
well, that the the thing with a lot of people struggling with for example depression. If they were to wait until they wanted to, they would often end up doing nothing, and later feel bad about having been unproductive that day. A tidy room generally can help with mental health, which is why it is a reoccurring suggestion to work towards it. A common pattern that arises with people that are in a difficult place emotionally is that they lack the energy to work on big, monolithic tasks. They aren't usually a productive thing to think of either way. Take "I will clean the entire apartment". It's a frustrating goal, there will always be more work since there was never a meaningful scope to it, and no sense of accomplishment in pausing it. In contrast, take a simple, well-defined task with a defined scope and a clear time frame, such as "I will clear this particular spot on the floor today/right now/in one hour". It has a comparably clear end, you make obvious, measurable progress doing it, and time frame and actions needed are rather clearly laid out with little risk of needing to spend mental energy on it.
>im still eating with the plates
first off, very good you are taking care of yourself! Second, you can do it later today, anon. None of these are meant as in "you need to do them immediately", but I urge people to do it the same day.

Okay so the bad news is that one of my favorite cook books, the Silver Spoon (Il cucchiaio d'argento) by Phaidon Press. It is a standard book for italian cooking, and apart from a decent amount of more involved recipes it features a good amount of recipes that are very pantry friendly, especially the dried pasta and risotto section. Whether ingredients like parmesan are affordable strongly depends on where you live though, so that may be a constraint. Both of these have in common that a great deal of them rely on <10 ingredients. Most of them require you to work a pot and a pan though.
Yesterday I made caccio e pepe which is not in the book, but to give you an idea (except I had to sub peccorino with parmesan since that is what I have with me atm).
It was about (since I had to weigh my ingredients)
150g dried spaghetti (537)
15g butter (107)
25g Parmesan (93)
salt, freshly ground pepper
total ~740kcal, 2 servings, requires a single pan and something to stir with.
Use a pan large enough to hold dried spaghetti. Add enough water to cover the pasta (1 in maybe), add 1/8-1/4 tsp salt, bring to a boil at medium to high heat. Add spaghetti, stir and let the liquid reduce to the point it is almost entirely gone.
Add butter. If the pasta should have a bite but not be crunchy by the time it reduced. If it is still a little too firm, add a small amount of water and stir until reduced. You would end up with a puddle of starchy, cloudy water at the bottom of the pan. Once the pasta is done take it off the heat and stir in the grated cheese and ground pepper. The immense amount of starch in the water will emulsify the cheese into a sauce. Serve immediately.

>>28962838
In general, if you want simple meals that don't require much prep, aim for carbs. Beans and rice are very common a combination and at most require you to cook rice (a rice cooker pays off) and soak beans if you don't buy canned ones. The beans should have plenty of protein so what you need is some fresh produce on top. Frozen veggies will do, and the rest is a matter of spices, you can look for inspiration in various recipes online there.

Another note on pasta: the recipe I mentioned has the quirk that it uses only a single pot. The silver spoon has another one of that sort. There, you fry onions in a pot with butter until translucent, then toss in penne to cover them in the butter fat, and instead of boiling them normally you add stock ladle by ladle until the penne absorbed enough to be al dente, then add some saffron and parmesan for flavor and color. It is one of my favorite recipes, and if you have chicken stock at home requires you to only cut a single onion and the time it takes to stir the ingredients in a pot. So all that needs cleaning is a grater, a pot and a cooking spoon.

posts.com:
Most recipes I make avoid meat since I only get to buy groceries at irregular intervals, so I rely on dairy, eggs, legumes and such as my source of protein. Just a heads up.
Since I need to calorie count for the forseeable future I have a set of scales and weigh differences since I play it mostly by ear at this point. In other words I put whatever ingredient I want on the scales, tare it, take out what I need and put the container back on the scales (so I measure the negative weight you could say). That way I don't have any measurement cups to clean.

Eggs are immensely useful as well. Scrambled eggs are a good staple requiring anywhere from 2-4 ingredients depending on how you like them. Personally, I enjoy them either custardy or very thick, so I usually keep it to butter, milk, eggs with salt and pepper to taste, served on a country style bread slice. Onions (esp shallots or scallions) are a nice addition though.

You can make soups without any stock by using milk as a base. A stick blender allows you to turn broccoli, salt, and milk into a delicious cream soup with little effort and a few extras. Same works with potatoes, squash, and related vegetables. Curries that use curry paste or similar as a base are also rather convenient as it usually boils down to cutting veggies and meat, browning the meat, toasting the paste a bit, adding cocounut milk and waiting. Serve on rice.
